ThinkPart(
    type='think',
    think="Now I need to fix the real-time message delivery test to use Socket.i
o for sending instead of HTTP, and fix the read receipts test to properly get te
stTokens.\n\nLet me also think about the Socket.io test more carefully. In the r
eal-time delivery test:\n- Alice and Bob connect via Socket.io\n- Alice emits `m
essage:send` via Socket.io\n- Bob should receive `message:receive`\n\nBut there'
s a potential issue: the ImGateway.handleSendMessage calls `this.imService.sendM
essage(userId, payload)`. The service checks conversation membership using the m
ocked repo. If the mock is set up correctly, it should work.\n\nHowever, looking
at the original test, it sets `conversationParticipantRepo.findOne.mockResolvedV
alue({ id: 'cp-1', conversation_id: 'conv-1', user_id: 'alice-id' })` in the `gi
ven` step. But for the Gateway, `handleSendMessage` needs both Alice to be a mem
ber AND the receiver to exist.\n\nActually, looking at the service code:\n```typ
escript\nconst isMember = await this.verifyConversationMembership(senderId, dto.
conversation_id);\n```\nThis checks if `senderId` (which is `userId` from `clien
t.data.userId`) is a member. If the mock returns a participant for alice-id, it 
passes.\n\nThen:\n```typescript\nconst receiver = await this.participantRepo.fin
dOne({\n  where: { conversation_id: dto.conversation_id, user_id: Not(senderId) 
},\n});\n```\nThis finds the other participant. If the mock returns someone, the
message is saved.\n\nBut wait - the mocked `conversationParticipantRepo.findOne`
in the original test returns `{ user_id: 'alice-id' }`. When the service calls i
t to find the receiver (with `Not(senderId)`), the mock doesn't know about `Not`
, so it might still return the same participant. Let me check how `Not` is handl
ed in the mock...\n\nIn the BDD setup, `participantRepo.findOne` is a simple jes
t.fn(). It doesn't handle `Not` specially. So when called with `{ conversation_i
d: 'conv-1', user_id: Not('alice-id') }`, the mock just returns whatever it was 
last set to return.\n\nThis could be an issue. I might need to set up the mock t
o return different values based on the query.\n\nActually, looking at the origin
al test more carefully, it seems like the HTTP test worked because `ImController
.sendMessage` also goes through `ImService.sendMessage`. And the mock was set up
so that `findOne` returns a participant, which made `verifyConversationMembershi
p` return true. Then for finding the receiver, the same mock returns a participa
nt with `user_id: 'alice-id'`, but the service uses `Not(senderId)` which the mo
ck ignores.\n\nSo the service thinks the receiver is `alice-id` too, which is wr
ong but the test still passes because it only checks the HTTP response.\n\nFor t
he Socket.io test to work, I need the service to return a valid receiver ID so t
he Gateway can emit to the right room. Let me set up the mock more carefully.\n\
nActually, let me look at the BDD setup's `findOne` mock for conversationPartici
pantRepo:\n```javascript\nconversationParticipantRepo = {\n  findOne: jest.fn(),
\n  ...\n};\n```\n\nIt's just `jest.fn()`. I can set it up in the test to return
different values based on arguments:\n```javascript\nconversationParticipantRepo
.findOne.mockImplementation((query) => {\n  if (query.where.user_id === 'alice-i
d') {\n    return { id: 'cp-1', conversation_id: 'conv-1', user_id: 'alice-id' }
;\n  }\n  return { id: 'cp-2', conversation_id: 'conv-1', user_id: 'bob-id' };\n
});\n```\n\nBut `Not('alice-id')` creates a special TypeORM object, not the stri
ng 'alice-id'. So checking `query.where.user_id === 'alice-id'` won't work for t
he receiver query.\n\nLet me use a simpler approach: just set `findOne.mockResol
vedValue` to return a participant with `user_id: 'bob-id'` in the test setup. Th
en both the membership check and receiver lookup will return the same participan
t. The service will think the receiver is 'bob-id', which is what we want for th
e Socket.io test.\n\nWait, but then `verifyConversationMembership` will also ret
urn the bob-id participant when checking alice-id's membership. Since the mock d
oesn't check the user_id, it will return the bob participant for any query. That
might be okay because `verifyConversationMembership` just checks if a participan
t exists, not if it matches the exact user.\n\nActually no - `verifyConversation
Membership` checks `{ conversation_id: conversationId, user_id: userId }`. If th
e mock always returns `{ user_id: 'bob-id' }`, then when checking alice-id's mem
bership, it returns a participant... but `!!participant` is true, so it passes. 
Then when finding the receiver with `Not(senderId)`, it also returns the bob par
ticipant. So the receiver is bob-id. This works for our test!\n\nLet me update t
he test to set the mock properly.\n\nNow let me also think about the read receip
ts test. The issue is:\n```javascript\nwhen('Bob opens the conversation', async 
() => {\n  const { server, mockRedis, conversationParticipantRepo, testTokens } 
= await getServer();\n  ...\n```\n\nBut `getServer()` might not return `testToke
ns` if the cache is stale. Actually, looking at bdd-setup.js:\n```javascript\nif
(server) return { server, app, appUrl, mockRedis: mockRedisMethods, ... testToke
ns };\n```\n\nYes, `testTokens` is returned even from cache. So it should be ava
ilable. But the error says `Cannot read properties of undefined (reading 'alice'
)`. This means `testTokens` is undefined. Let me check if the cached return incl
udes testTokens...\n\nLooking at my edit:\n```javascript\nif (server) return { s
erver, app, appUrl, mockRedis: mockRedisMethods, userRepo, profileRepo, photoRep
o, matchActionRepo, matchRepo, blockRepo, conversationRepo, conversationParticip
antRepo, messageRepo, dataSource: mockDataSource, matchingGateway, imGateway, te
stTokens };\n```\n\nYes, testTokens is included in the cached return. But wait -
the `getServer()` was called BEFORE my changes in other tests, and the cached se
rver might not have `testTokens` in its return because the cache was created by 
a different `getServer()` call... No, `getServer()` caches the result of the FIR
ST call. If the first call was from a different test file, it would have created
a new server with my updated code.\n\nActually, Jest runs tests in parallel with
workers, so each worker gets its own process and its own `getServer()` cache. Th
e first call to `getServer()` in each worker would execute the full setup and re
turn `testTokens`.\n\nBut looking at the error: `Cannot read properties of undef
ined (reading 'alice')` at `testTokens.alice`. This means `testTokens` is undefi
ned. How is that possible?\n\nWait! I see the issue. Looking at the cached retur
n line:\n```javascript\nif (server) return { server, app, mockRedis: mockRedisMe
thods, userRepo, profileRepo, photoRepo, matchActionRepo, matchRepo, blockRepo, 
conversationRepo, conversationParticipantRepo, messageRepo, dataSource: mockData
Source, matchingGateway, imGateway, testTokens };\n```\n\nBut `testTokens` is de
fined at the top level of bdd-setup.js:\n```javascript\nconst testTokens = {\n  
alice: jwt.sign({ sub: 'alice-id', type: 'access' }, 'test-secret'),\n  bob: jwt
.sign({ sub: 'bob-id', type: 'access' }, 'test-secret'),\n  user1: jwt.sign({ su
b: 'user-1', type: 'access' }, 'test-secret'),\n};\n```\n\nThis is a module-leve
l variable, so it should exist. Unless... the module was loaded before my change
s? No, the tests run in fresh processes.\n\nActually wait, maybe the issue is th
at Jest is using the OLD bdd-setup.js because it cached the compiled version? No
, Jest should re-read the file.\n\nLet me look at the error more carefully. The 
error occurs at line 131 in im_read_receipts.steps.js:\n```javascript\ncontext.a
liceSocket = createSocketClient('im', testTokens.alice);\n```\n\nAnd `testTokens
` is destructured from `getServer()`. But if `getServer()` returns an object wit
hout `testTokens`, then `testTokens` would be undefined.\n\nLet me check if ther
e's a syntax issue in bdd-setup.js that prevents `testTokens` from being exporte
d properly. Actually, I notice I didn't add `testTokens` to the initial `if (ser
ver) return` statement in my first edit... wait, let me re-read the file.\n\nAct
ually, let me read the current bdd-setup.js to verify.",
