    think='There are multiple issues:\n\n1. **im_conversation_list**: Still fail
ing with `undefined !== 0`. The `innerJoin` mock was added but now there\'s a ne
w issue. Looking at the error, `context.response.body.code` is undefined. This m
eans the response body itself might be undefined or the request failed. The Nest
JS error log shows `this.participantRepo.createQueryBuilder(...).innerJoin is no
t a function` - wait, this is still happening! Let me check the im_conversation_
list test more carefully. It sets up its own `createQueryBuilder` mock, but does
it also need to update the cached repo? Actually, the test creates a NEW mock im
plementation for `createQueryBuilder` which DOES include `innerJoin` now. So why
is the error still happening?\n\nWait, looking at the error log more carefully: 
the `[Nest] ERROR [ExceptionsHandler] this.participantRepo.createQueryBuilder(..
.).innerJoin is not a function` appears BEFORE the test results. This might be f
rom a DIFFERENT test that also calls `getConversations`. Let me check which othe
r tests call `/conversations`.\n\nActually, looking at the failing tests:\n- im_
conversation_list.steps.js: both tests fail\n- im_read_receipts.steps.js: both t
ests fail  \n- im_real_time_message_delivery.steps.js: Socket.io test fails\n\nF
or im_conversation_list, the response has `body.code` undefined. This suggests t
he HTTP request returned an error response (maybe 500), and supertest\'s respons
e body doesn\'t have `.code`. Let me check what the actual response looks like.\
n\nActually, in NestJS, when an unhandled exception occurs, supertest gets the e
rror response. The response body might be `{ statusCode: 500, message: \'Interna
l server error\' }` instead of `{ code: 0, data: ... }`.\n\nFor the `innerJoin` 
error, I need to check if there are other test files that call `/conversations` 
but don\'t mock `createQueryBuilder` with `innerJoin`. Looking at the test files
... `im_start_chatting_after_match.steps.js` might also call `/conversations`.\n
\nActually, wait. The `im_conversation_list` test creates its own `createQueryBu
ilder` mock with `innerJoin`. But looking at the test, it does:\n```javascript\n
conversationParticipantRepo.createQueryBuilder.mockImplementation(() => { ... })
;\n```\n\nThis should override the default mock from bdd-setup. So why does `get
Conversations` still fail?\n\nLet me trace through the code. In `im.service.ts`,
`getConversations` does:\n```typescript\nconst participantQb = this.participantR
epo\n  .createQueryBuilder("cp")\n  .innerJoin("conversations", "c", "c.id = cp.
conversation_id")\n  ...\n```\n\nBut the test\'s mock `createQueryBuilder` retur
ns a qb object. However, `createQueryBuilder` is called ON the repository, and t
he repository\'s `createQueryBuilder` in bdd-setup.js is:\n```javascript\nconver
sationParticipantRepo = {\n  findOne: jest.fn(),\n  find: jest.fn(),\n  create: 
jest.fn(),\n  save: jest.fn(),\n  update: jest.fn().mockResolvedValue({}),\n  cr
eateQueryBuilder: jest.fn().mockImplementation(createMockParticipantQb),\n};\n``
`\n\nIn the test, it overrides `createQueryBuilder` with a custom implementation
. But wait - `getServer()` returns the SAME cached repos across tests. If a prev
ious test modified `conversationParticipantRepo.createQueryBuilder`, then the ne
xt test\'s override should still work... unless the previous test\'s mock is som
ehow sticky.\n\nActually, looking at the `im_conversation_list` test\'s `given` 
step, it sets up the mock but then the `when` step calls `server.get(\'/conversa
tions\')`. If the mock is correctly set up, it should work.\n\nHmm, let me think
about this differently. Maybe the issue is that `getConversations` now uses `inn
erJoin` with STRING arguments:\n```typescript\n.innerJoin("conversations", "c", 
"c.id = cp.conversation_id")\n```\n\nWait, in TypeORM, `.innerJoin()` can take d
ifferent overloads. For joining with another table using a raw condition, it sho
uld be:\n```typescript\n.innerJoin(ConversationEntity, "c", "c.id = cp.conversat
ion_id")\n```\n\nBut I used `"conversations"` as a string! TypeORM\'s `innerJoin
` with a string as the first argument might interpret it as a relation name or a
subquery, not as a table name. For raw SQL table joining, I might need to use `.
innerJoin()` differently.\n\nActually, looking at TypeORM docs:\n- `innerJoin(en
tityOrProperty, alias, condition)` \n- If first arg is a string that\'s not an e
ntity or relation, it might fail.\n\nBut in the service, I wrote:\n```typescript
\n.innerJoin("conversations", "c", "c.id = cp.conversation_id")\n```\n\nThis is 
wrong! TypeORM\'s `innerJoin` expects either:\n1. An entity class: `.innerJoin(C
onversationEntity, "c", "c.id = cp.conversation_id")`\n2. A relation property pa
th: `.innerJoin("cp.conversation", "c")` (if there\'s a relation defined)\n\nSin
ce I used a string "conversations", TypeORM might not recognize it. But actually
, TypeORM also supports raw SQL subqueries as strings... I\'m not entirely sure.
\n\nWait, but the original error was `innerJoin is not a function`, which was be
cause the mock didn\'t have it. Now the mock has it, but maybe TypeORM\'s actual
