ThinkPart(
    type='think',
    think="Now I see the issue clearly!\n\nIn test 1's `when` step:\n```javascri
pt\nconversationParticipantRepo.findOne = jest.fn().mockImplementation((...args)
=> {\n  return Promise.resolve({\n    id: 'cp-alice',\n    user_id: 'alice-id',\
n  });\n});\n```\n\nThis REPLACES `findOne` on the shared `conversationParticipa
ntRepo` object. Since `getServer()` caches the server and repos across tests, th
is replacement persists into test 2.\n\nIn test 2's `and` step:\n```javascript\n
conversationParticipantRepo.findOne.mockResolvedValue({\n  id: 'cp-1',\n  user_i
d: 'bob-id',\n});\n```\n\nThis calls `mockResolvedValue` on the REPLACED jest.fn
from test 1. As we verified, `mockResolvedValue` overrides `mockImplementation`.
So now `findOne` returns `Promise.resolve({ user_id: 'bob-id' })`.\n\nIn test 2'
s `when` step:\n```javascript\nconversationParticipantRepo.findOne.mockResolvedV
alue({\n  id: 'cp-1',\n  user_id: 'bob-id',\n});\n```\n\nThis sets it to `bob-id
` again! It should be `alice-id` because Bob is calling `markAsRead`, so the OTH
ER participant should be Alice.\n\nThe fix is simple: in test 2's `when` step, s
et `mockResolvedValue` to return `alice-id` instead of `bob-id`.\n\nBut wait, th
ere's another issue. The `[DEBUG TEST] findOne called with:` logs don't appear f
or test 2's `markAsRead`. That's because test 2's `when` step doesn't replace `f
indOne` with a function that has `console.log`. It just calls `mockResolvedValue
`. So the `findOne` is called but without the debug log.\n\nActually, looking at
the git diff, test 1's `when` step DOES replace `findOne` with a `mockImplementa
tion` that has a `console.log`. And test 2's `when` step just calls `mockResolve
dValue` on that same function.\n\nSo the fix is:\n1. In test 2's `when` step, ch
ange `user_id: 'bob-id'` to `user_id: 'alice-id'`\n2. Remove the debug logs from
test 1 and from `im.service.ts` and `bdd-setup.js`\n\nWait, but test 1 is suppos
ed to set the mock to `alice-id` because Bob is the one calling `markAsRead` (vi
a HTTP), so the other participant is Alice. But test 1 ONLY checks the HTTP resp
onse status, not the actual `otherUserId`.\n\nAnd test 2's `when` step should al
so set the mock to `alice-id` because Bob (via socket) is calling `markAsRead`, 
so the other participant is Alice.\n\nLet me also think about the broader issue:
test 1's `when` step REPLACES `findOne` with a new function. This is a side effe
ct that leaks into test 2. A better approach would be to NOT replace `findOne` i
n test 1, but just use `mockResolvedValue`. And in `bdd-setup.js`, we should add
a `clearAllMocks` or reset mechanism between tests.\n\nBut for now, let me just 
fix the immediate issue:\n1. Change test 2's `when` step to use `alice-id`\n2. R
emove the debug logs\n3. Consider resetting the mock between tests\n\nActually, 
looking more carefully at test 1, it already replaces `findOne` in the `when` st
ep. If we don't want side effects between tests, we should save and restore the 
original `findOne`. But let's keep it simple for now.\n\nLet me fix test 2's `wh
en` step first.",
    encrypted=None
)
